I"õ<p>In order to create a table, the most common way is to use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">\begin{table}</code>. And then <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">\begin{tabular}{}</code> where we can specify how many columns there are and what their alignments are. The common ones used are <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">{l c c}</code> if there are three columns or <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">{l *{5}{c} m{4cm}}</code> if there are seven. In order to add notes to the table, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">\multicolumn</code> is helpful. Below is an example:</p>
<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>\begin{table}
\begin{tabular}{l *{5}{c} m{4cm}}
\hline
\textbf{Code} &amp; \textbf{States} &amp; \textbf{DtR} &amp; \textbf{CD} &amp; \textbf{Signed} &amp; \textbf{Enacted} &amp; \textbf{Law Stipulations} \\
\hline
03 &amp; Arkansas &amp; yes (wp) &amp; yes (wp) &amp; &amp; no &amp; \\
\hline
\multicolumn{7}{l}{\footnotesize DtR: Duty to Retreat} \\
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>The end result is displayed as below:
<img src="/images/table.jpg" alt="Table" title="Table" /></p>
